<subSubSection id="9F51B357AAD9D5481E9FFDFBE954A5F6" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="habit and habitat">
<paragraph id="9BE51C6DCF97812D37765FFDAD4DFF97" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Habit and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6F0CA538AABF1DEBD4C057B5BBBF8325" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Scattered to gregarious on the ground covered with dead leaves in temperate mixed forests, from summer to autumn.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E948ABEB6CB7F65768327652A669E346" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="55A413C5F66FC2155C4B7E1E8E6041BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A7F125CABB36036749912C0430B2E86A" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">The Republic of Korea.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3D348501EB70A0F28CB3B52645EC9A4D" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="74AAD322F3BA3B9156EF3A0F1844C1C4" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Remark.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1FEB95E46E7905474E80584D2A6B1B3D" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">
<taxonomicName id="154AC68FB6E7FF83B5C27E0A59108013" authorityName="J. S. Kim &amp; Y. W. Lim" authorityYear="2022" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Collybiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Collybiopsis subumbilicata" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="subumbilicata">
<emphasis id="48F60848BFE38BFA18F7927B4745BC37" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Collybiopsis subumbilicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4AED3006EB9675C1E1F9650B7A86A3E4" genus="Co." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Co. villosipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="villosipes">
<emphasis id="D833971F02BAAD4766CD2FFB59C93CCF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Co. villosipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Cleland) R.H. Petersen. 
<taxonomicName id="DD4A744FFAFC811BE795659F754DBDF5" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Collybiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Collybiopsis villosipes" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="villosipes">
<emphasis id="FCCDB4DA131EEE06FC72B7CAF25BDEE5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Collybiopsis villosipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="5C7782FD2C43CB498970E890E4C62FDA" genus="Co." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Co. subumbilicata" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="subumbilicata">
<emphasis id="C0E27801432276FFBFB1792CF8F55973" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Co. subumbilicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by fewer and brownish lamellae (also lamellulae), a noninsititious, light-colored stipe, larger basidiospores (6.5-10.5 
<normalizedToken id="89D4DC4463A485175E6E2A6619802CC6" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.5-4.5 
<normalizedToken id="4F76DFA21585718E8041B7BF8A7C259D" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) and basidia (25-34 
<normalizedToken id="19AD8C68E8FD3D91B5718BC1AAE73790" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6.5-7.5 
<normalizedToken id="DD211C40578C8D1212E458F88F618DE3" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="9799ECBED8E925C4C7F251A558EDEA0B" author="Desjardin, DE" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="141 - 148" refId="B9" refString="Desjardin, DE, Halling, RE, Perry, BA, 1997. Gymnopus villosipes -a common collybioid agaric from California. Mycotaxon 64: 141 - 148" title="Gymnopus villosipes - a common collybioid agaric from California." volume="64" year="1997">Desjardin et al. 1997</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName id="C211F3116BC730B41617DDF3711D605F" genus="Co." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Co. subumbilicata" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="subumbilicata">
<emphasis id="DFBD1540D7E61A424078F5884879BA21" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Co. subumbilicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is phylogenetically close to 
<taxonomicName id="471CA5D386E64D76958713D7ACA963FE" genus="Co." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Co. biformis" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="biformis">
<emphasis id="8CEDF7C41C51C53AA621F19820D706EC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Co. biformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="182D94637887BCA8AB30A623CFBF25CC" genus="Co." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Co. disjuncta" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="disjuncta">
<emphasis id="30B391A68B842E98FFD16AC794F8898B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Co. disjuncta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(R.H. Petersen &amp; K.W. Hughes) R.H. Petersen &amp; K.W. Hughes. 
<taxonomicName id="924BAD7B69D3094B247C1505BFCA58F4" authorityName="R.H.Petersen" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Peck" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Collybiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Collybiopsis biformis" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="biformis">
<emphasis id="67E6285551B6C2F16B5A709521623318" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Collybiopsis biformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4535BBD31B9F914C14343E1A09BDF2AC" genus="Co." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Co. subumbilicata" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="subumbilicata">
<emphasis id="D9DD608154F3FD062C67F98DCFCA7C0D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Co. subumbilicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be distinguished by elongated basidiospores (6.4-9.2 
<normalizedToken id="15763AC051D9367A85DB260238E95480" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.4-4.8 
<normalizedToken id="93A8DD5BFDC6D76C70CE664F8FAC51C2" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
), thicker basidia (6-7 
<normalizedToken id="A00391C44A9B16E89561DDB346C4C32C" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
thick) and cheilocystidia (6-12 
<normalizedToken id="F7A3C349448364453E482BCBC2218A37" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
thick) (
<bibRefCitation id="03BE7C04CDC2EEB79AEFD5C877D142E0" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/3752425" author="Morgan, AP" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="201 - 212" refId="B35" refString="Morgan, AP, 1905. North American species of Marasmius. Journal of Mycology 11 (5): 201 - 212, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/3752425" title="North American species of Marasmius." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3752425" volume="11" year="1905">Morgan 1905</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="16F9B754314673C35D33563DB915821B" author="Mata, JL" journalOrPublisher="FEMS Microbiology Letters" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" refId="B27" refString="Mata, JL, 2002. Taxonomy and systematics of Lentinula, Gymnopus and Rhodocollybia (Agaricales, Fungi) with emphasis on oak forests of southern Costa Rica. PhD Thesis, University of Tennessee, Knoxville." title="Taxonomy and systematics of Lentinula, Gymnopus and Rhodocollybia (Agaricales, Fungi) with emphasis on oak forests of southern Costa Rica. PhD Thesis, University of Tennessee, Knoxville." year="2002">Mata 2002</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="F1E7C49A65CC80BCD871FB817A30C3DA" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Collybiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Collybiopsis disjuncta" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="disjuncta">
<emphasis id="A8875102C7235E5B06DB03F4D82A564A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Collybiopsis disjuncta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="431D36D6A4ED6907CBFED58B666D8DB8" genus="Co." kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Co. subumbilicata" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" rank="species" species="subumbilicata">
<emphasis id="66E341AAF3411B9D3CF40DA2FF8BCC68" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="79">Co. subumbilicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a smaller pileus (7-12 mm) with olivaceous tint, pinkish lamellae, slender stipe (0.5-1 mm thick), bigger basidiospores (6-7.5 
<normalizedToken id="956F5ABF52ADB7BA485AB3873E327F7B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-3.5 
<normalizedToken id="66FD27EAD5BBF67D9E41126626F173E3" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
), bigger basidia (22-34 
<normalizedToken id="05E2B699EE61219FF67D8220C27400B8" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7 
<normalizedToken id="4E3D8CC98E49642B27A74ED5112FC8A7" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
), and a seldom incrusted pileipellis (
<bibRefCitation id="0FA5451CC213C6EFC6513828D64CDD0D" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2509/naf2014.009.003" author="Petersen, R" journalOrPublisher="North American Fungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="79" pagination="1 - 22" refId="B42" refString="Petersen, R, Hughes, K, 2014. New North American species of Gymnopus. North American Fungi 9 (0): 1 - 22, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2509/naf2014.009.003" title="New North American species of Gymnopus." url="https://doi.org/10.2509/naf2014.009.003" volume="9" year="2014">Petersen and Hughes 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
